m Methodism's Wesleyan beginnings to the prominence of women in local societies, the construction of African Methodism, the diverse social profile of Methodist men, and contests over the movement's future, Andrews charts Methodism's metamorphosis from a British missionary organization to a fully Americanized church. Weaving together narrative and analysis, Andrews explains Methodism's extraordinary popular appeal in rich and compelling new detail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAbolitionism.  aAbsalom Jones.  aAfrican Methodist Episcopal Church.  aAfrican Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.  aAmericans.  aAnglicanism.  aAnthony Benezet.  aBaptists.  aBenjamin Chew.  aBenjamin Rush.  aBritish America.  aCalvinism.  aCatholic Church.  aCharles Wesley.  aChristian Methodist Episcopal Church.  aChristian revival.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aChurch attendance.  aChurch of England.  aClergy.  aCongregational church.  aDoctrine.  aDutch Reformed Church.  aEnthusiasm.  aEpiscopal Church (United States).  aEvangelical Methodist Church.  aEvangelicalism.  aFrancis Asbury.  aFreeborn Garrettson.  aGeorge Whitefield.  aGod.  aGreat Awakening.  aHarold Bloom.  aHuguenot.  aItinerant preacher.  aJames O'Kelly.  aJohn Dickins.  aJohn Wesley.  aLaity.  aLorenzo Dow.  aLutheranism.  aMarital status.  aMethodism.  aMinister (Christianity).  aMissionary (LDS Church).  aMissionary.  aMr.  aNarrative.  aOld Testament.  aOrdination.  aParish.  aPastor.  aPhilip Embury.  aPiety.  aPolemic.  aPolitician.  aPrayer meeting.  aPrayer.  aPreacher.  aPresbyterianism.  aProtestantism.  aPsalms.  aPuritans.  aQuakers.  aRadicalism (historical).  aReligion.  aReligious Affections.  aR